LUT Analysis

Yuyang Zhao

Motivation

Given a LUT that represents some mapping \(f:\mathbb{R}^3\to\mathbb{R}^3\), I want to analyze some of its properties. One idea is to represent the LUT in some 2 dimensional plot. Some ways to do this include projecting all the (r,g,b) vectors onto some plane, or examining a cross-section plane of the LUT. The former method represents all data points, which is too much information at a time, while the latter will likely represent too little information at a time.

To get the best of both worlds, I will take a slice of the LUT bounded by two parallel planes and project this slice onto a 2D plot. I can setup the orientation of the slice by defining a normal vector \(\vec{n}\) orthogonal to a plane \(P\) crossing the origin. I can define the slice itself by translating \(P\) along \(P^\perp=\{t\vec{n}:t\in\mathbb{R}\}\) to get two new planes that bound the slice. Finally I can setup the location of the slice by translating these two planes by some vector in space.

Implementation

rm(list=ls())
vector_dot <- function(x, y) {
  return(sum(x * y))
}
vector_norm <- function(x) {
  return(sqrt(vector_dot(x, x)))
}
vector_proj <- function(n) {
  return(function(x) {
    return(vector_dot(x, n)/vector_dot(n, n) * n)
  })
}
vector_perp <- function(n) {
  return(function(x) {
    return(x - vector_proj(n)(x))
  })
}
cross_product <- function(x, y) {
  v1 <- x[2] * y[3] - x[3] * y[2]
  v2 <- x[3] * y[1] - x[1] * y[3]
  v3 <- x[1] * y[2] - x[2] * y[1]
  return(c(v1, v2, v3))
}

Let’s first implement a special case where I’m not interested in relocating the slice. Notice that the slice is bounded by 2 planes orthogonal to \(\vec{n}\). Thus a point \(\vec{v}\) lies in the slice if \(proj_n(\vec{v})\) lies in the slice.

n <- c(1, 1, 1)
norm_n <- vector_norm(n)
proj_n <- vector_proj(n)
perp_n <- vector_perp(n)

data_subset <- function(data, bounds) {
  mapply(FUN=function(r, g, b) {
    v <- proj_n(c(r, g, b))
    norm_v <- vector_norm(v)
    return(bounds[1] <= norm_v && norm_v <= bounds[2])
  }, data[,1], data[,2], data[,3])
}

The code above sets \(\vec{n}:=(1,1,1)\) which is an interesting normal vector because \[ proj_{(1,1,1)}(r,g,b) =\frac{r+g+b}{3}\begin{bmatrix}1\\1\\1\end{bmatrix} =\begin{bmatrix}\bar{v}\\\bar{v}\\\bar{v}\end{bmatrix},\ \bar{v}=mean(r,g,b) \] Thus each component of the projection become the arithmetic mean of (r,g,b) i.e the brightness. Notice how we use this in our data_subset function to essentially find all the points that lie in a certain brightness bounds.

Next I will define a new projection transformation that “flattens” our slice into the plane \(P\) orthogonal to \(\vec{n}\). It’s easier to define this as a diagonal matrix \(D\) in terms of some basis for \(P\). We’ll use a change of basis matrix \(R\) to apply the transformation. To preserve angles, we want \(R\) to be a rotation matrix. A natural choice for \(R\) would be the matrix that rotates \(\hat{n}\) to \(\vec{e_3}=(0,0,1)\). This source helps us find such a matrix.

I <- cbind(c(1,0,0), c(0,1,0), c(0,0,1))
n_hat <- n / vector_norm(n)
v <- cross_product(n_hat, I[,3])
c <- vector_dot(n_hat, I[,3])
v_cross <- rbind(
  c(0, -v[3], v[2]),
  c(v[3], 0, -v[1]),
  c(-v[2], v[1], 0)
)
R <- I + v_cross + v_cross %*% v_cross / (1 + c)
D <- cbind(I[,1], I[,2], c(0, 0, 0))
A <- D %*% R

plot_slice <- function(lut, t, r) {
  bounds <- c(t-r, t+r) * norm_n
  slice <- lut[data_subset(lut, bounds),]
  
  slice_flattened <- mapply(FUN=function(r, g, b) {A %*% c(r, g, b)}, slice$r, slice$b, slice$g)
  slice_flattened <- matrix(slice_flattened, ncol=3, byrow=TRUE)
  
  colouring <- mapply(FUN=function(r, g, b) {
    colour_range <- 0.8
    colour <- colour_range * c(r, g, b) + (1 - colour_range) / 2
    return(rgb(colour[1], colour[2], colour[3]))
  }, slice$r, slice$g, slice$b)
  plot(slice_flattened[,1], slice_flattened[,2],
       xlim=c(-1, 1), ylim=c(-1, 1), asp=1, col=colouring, pch=20, cex=0.5)
}

Flattened Slice

In this case we can analyze the hue and chroma of a given brightness.

par(mfrow=c(3, 3), mar=rep(0.1, 4))
# Build images -> save them at .png format
#png(file="slice%02d.png", width=640, height=640)
num_images <- 9
offset <- ceiling(num_images / 2) - num_images / 2
for (i in c(1:num_images)) {
  t <- (offset + i - 1) / num_images
  plot_slice(k5207_print_lut, t, 0.01)
}
